om/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2922<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/18/03 3:40:57 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=162.topic>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Giant Spring.</span><hr size=1> To escape the Earths gravity you need to reach 11.2 km per second. Whats wrong with storing the energy to accelerate a payload to such a velocity then releasing it quickly?<br>
<br>
Is there any reason why a giant close-coiled round wire helical compression spring wouldn't work?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.engineerstoolbox.com/doc/etb/mod/stat1/spring/spring_closed.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
It's tower straight structure makes it ideal to withstand the force of gravity. Wrapped around a steel tower for support it could be scaled up to any size required. Not that the local steelworks is likely to have the means of building it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1847<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/20/03 4:49:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=162.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Giant Spring.</span><hr size=1> Any math wiz care to calculate the size it would need to be to <br>
loft 100 tons into LEO? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zentrander>Zentrander</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 199<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/20/03 4:58:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=162.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Giant Spring.</span><hr size=1> doesnt launch propulsion kind of have to be sustained?  As time went on, the object would be slowed more and more by gravity, and i would wager that the speed needed to counter this would put a huge strain on the vehicle.  <br>
<br>
If you had constant thrust, you dont have to be as fast, because you are always pushing against gravity. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 743<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/20/03 8:58:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=162.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Giant Spring.</span><hr size=1> A main drawback to using a spring to launch heavy payloads into orbit would be its tendency to want to jump off the ground.  I can't see the components being used to anchor it lasting a very long time.   I envision something like a deep pit being dug out and filled with concrete with the suitable anchoring mechanisms imbedded in it but you'd probably have to replace that concrete and its imbedded mechanisms more often than you'd care to. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>doesnt launch propulsion kind of have to be sustained?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
All that matters is that you can impart escape velocity to the payload.  As long as the force transferred by the spring was sufficient to overcome gravity and drag it should work.   It would basically be like a rail gun but instead of using electricity or an initial volley of gas, it would just use the potential energy stored in the spring.    <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2953<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/21/03 12:34:38 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=162.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Giant Spring.</span><hr size=1> It suddenly came to me one evening. If the wire diameter and spacing are the same then taking the standing compression impact of the payload into account it's quite simple. The spring expands roughly half it's height. It does this in less than a second. Let's say .5 second. So if you have a really thickly wired compression spring 11.2km tall it would probably accelerate a fair sized payload to escape velocity. Too much payload and the spring will lose too much of its stored energy supporting the mass as the weight compresses the thing down. Still, it wouldn't matter if only a ton was launched. You could use a counter weight to recompress it for another launches. The thicker the wire the faster the decompression. If I knew how fast a spring 'recoils' then I could be more accurate but half a second sounds conservative enough. When you see them they look almost instantaneous.<br>
Supposing it takes a tenth of a second for a compression spring to fire, then just over 2 kilometres of spring would be enough. Assuming you only want to reach orbit where it could use rockets to take over the job and not send it interplanetary, then under a kilometre might be enough. That sounds well within human engineering limitations. Now tell me I'm nuts because it can't be that easy. Have I missed something vital?<br>
