1. Air resistance. One of the problems with launchers of this type (i.e. railguns and mass drivers) is that they lose a ton of velocity fighting air. Concievably, you could dig your spring silo into the top of Mt. Everest, which would help a lot, but still you will lose a significant fraction. Most likely you will have to include a rocket on your payload, and then you have to calculate springing the mass of the fuel and such as well.<br>
2. Shape memory on the macro scale. My fear is that if you have a 3m thick steel rod, and bend it one way, it is not going to rebound, like a similiarly shaped 3mm thick verson would. Imagine bending a steel girder. It stays bent.<br>
3. Metal fatigue. Your putting incredible forces on this piece of metal nad it will corespondingly wear out pretty fast. It may be prohibitvely expensive to regularly construct replacement mega-springs.<br>
