A steel girder a kilometre long would probably bend. We are scaling up the whole thing. You could be right ofcourse. The material at higher dimensions might not respond to bending in the same fashion as a small spring. Still, I've seen a few large compression springs in trucks suspension systems that are really heavy and they are exactly the same in shape as tiny springs only a few millimetres long. I don't know if there is any physical limit to scaling them up. I was hoping someone else might. I'll do a few searches and see what I can find out.<br>
